HEADWORD: Pyridine
<hw>Pyr"i*dine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From Gr. <?/
fire.]</ety> <fld>(Physiol. Chem.)</fld> <def>A nitrogenous base,
<chform>C5H5N</chform>, obtained from the distillation of bone oil or
coal tar, and by the decomposition of certain alkaloids, as a colorless
liquid with a peculiar pungent odor. It is the nucleus of a large number
of organic substances, among which several vegetable alkaloids, as
nicotine and certain of the ptoma⟦ium⟧nes, may be mentioned. See
<er>Lutidine</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pyridyl</ent>⟦br⟧
